Description¶

Background and Context¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Data Description¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

Data Dictionary¶

  • CustomerId: Unique ID which is assigned to each customer
  • Surname: Last name of the customer
  • CreditScore: It defines the credit history of the customer.
  • Geography: A customer’s location
  • Gender: It defines the Gender of the customer
  • Age: Age of the customer
  • Tenure: Number of years for which the customer has been with the bank
  • NumOfProducts: It refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.
  • Balance: Account balance
  • HasCrCard: It is a categorical variable that decides whether the customer has a credit card or not.
  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary
  • isActiveMember: It is a categorical variable that decides whether the customer is an active member

""" Function to check missing values count and its percentage"""


def missing_check(df):
    total = (
        df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    )  # total number of null values
    percent = (df.isnull().sum() / df.isnull().count()).sort_values(
        ascending=False
    )  # percentage of values that are null
    missing_data = pd.concat(
        [total, percent], axis=1, keys=["Total", "Percent"]
    )  # putting the above two together
    return missing_data  # return the dataframe

Outlier Treatment¶

Identify outliers and treat it if needed

For this analysis any data points above 4 times of IQR is considers as outliers.

In [11]:
# This function helps to identify outlier for a given column.


def IQR4(column, cname):
    """Gives list that is greater than
    4 times inter quartile range.
    """
    quartiles = np.quantile(column[column.notnull()], [0.25, 0.75])
    power_4iqr = 4 * (quartiles[1] - quartiles[0])
    print(f"Q1 = {quartiles[0]}, Q3 = {quartiles[1]},4*IQR = {power_4iqr}")
    outlier_powers = custDataAttr.loc[
        np.abs(column - column.median()) > power_4iqr, cname
    ]
    return outlier_powers


def IQR4Value(column, cname):
    """Gives list that is greater than
    4 times inter quartile range.
    """
    quartiles = np.quantile(column[column.notnull()], [0.25, 0.75])
    power_4iqr = 4 * (quartiles[1] - quartiles[0])
    return power_4iqr

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.

# Histograms give a good sense of the distribution of a variable.

# Box plot to tell if the distribution is symmetric or skewed and its central value, its variability, etc.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 5), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        kde=kde,
        ax=ax_hist2,
        bins=bins,
        palette="winter",
        hue="Exited",
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, hue="Exited"
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
        hue="Exited",
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Data analysis insights¶

  • All customers with more than two bank products churn out. This is a serious finding and require additional information. More details are needed from the business about the products details to make necessary recommendation.
  • Half of the customers from Germany churn. Addressing this issue will significantly boost the over all bank customer retention. Country specific program might help.
  • Women churn out lot more than men. Gender retention program might help.
  • Middle age group (45 to 60) churn more than other age group.
  • Active customers stay with the bank

Data Preprocessing¶

During the data preparation stage, raw data is transformed into an easily digestible format for efficient ML algorithms. Then, all features in the data set are normalized to the same scale (unit) for clustering.

  • There are no missing values, so no treatment is necessary.
  • There are outliers in Age and estimated salary columns. These outliers will not be removed for neural network classifier analysis.
  • However "Standard" normalization is applied to these columns along with balance and credit score,.
  • There are no duplicate rows.

Balance the data set¶

There are three ways to deal with the imbalanced data set.

  • Over sampling,
  • Under sampling, and
  • Class weights.

Over sampling and under sampling methods give more weight to particular classes by duplicating observations and giving more influence in the model fit. This usually happens in the training data set.

Class weights modifies the loss function by penalizing the classes with weights. This sacrifices ability to predict the lower weight class by biasing the model to favor more accurate predictions of the higher weighted class.

Class weights performs better than sampling techniques, so model class weights is used to balance the data.

Check Appendix for more details.

Transform data using column transformer in a pipeline¶

  • A pipeline is created with a processor for certain numerical columns and 2 processor for categorical columns
  • Columns that has outliers and significant variations are normalized using standard scaler.
  • Categorical columns (Gender and Geography) are encoded using "one hot encoder".
  • Data set is transformed using pipeline and used to build the model
In [28]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
# scaler = MinMaxScaler()

pipeline = Pipeline(
    steps=[
        (
            "Categorizer",
            ColumnTransformer(
                [
                    (
                        "Gender one hot encoder",
                        OneHotEncoder(categories="auto", drop="first"),
                        ["Gender"],
                    ),
                    (
                        "Geography one hot encoder",
                        OneHotEncoder(categories="auto", drop="first"),
                        ["Geography"],
                    ),
                ],
                remainder="passthrough",
                n_jobs=1,
            ),
        ),
        ("Normalizer", scaler),
    ]
)

Building Artificial Neural Network.¶

  • ANN has one hidden layer and one output layer.
  • For hidden layer,
    • Relu function is used as the activation function because of its ability to learn nonlinear functions.
    • "70% of the number of dimension" is the formula used to choose number of neurons, so 0.7 X 11 =~ 8 is chosen for input. This formula is identified with number of trial and error run.
  • For output layer,
    • Sigmoid functions is used as the activation function because this model is used for binary classification.
    • Number of neuron is one.
  • Decided not to use "Dropout" regularization as it degraded the model performance.
  • For Gradient Descent tuning,
    • adam algorithm is used to find optimal weights.
    • binary_crossentropy loss function is used with in adam algorithm
    • Accuracy metric is evaluated as a criteria for model improvement.

Check Appendix for more details.

relumodel.add(Dense(1, activation="sigmoid", name="Output_layer"))

relumodel.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["Accuracy"])

Class weights¶

Apply class weight to compensate imbalanced data.

0 means No ( Customer did not leave the bank which is 80% of dataset ) and 1 means Yes ( Customer left the bank which is 20% of dataset)

Treat every instance of class 1 as 4 instances of class 0. This means that loss function assign higher value to these instances. Hence, the loss becomes a weighted average, where the weight of each sample is specified by class_weight and its corresponding class.

In bank dataset, class 0 is 80% and class 1 is 20%

So class 0 weight is 1 and class 1 weight is 4 (80/20)

In [36]:
class_weight = {0: 1.0, 1: 4}

Early stopping¶

Early stopping is used to stop training when a monitored metric has stopped improving.

In [37]:
# Early stopping
earlystop = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
    monitor="val_loss",
    min_delta=0,
    patience=15,
    verbose=0,
    mode="min",
    restore_best_weights=True,
)

Train the model¶

  • 50 samples are passed per gradient update.
  • 100 iteration is executed to tune the weights.
  • 20% of the training data to be used as validation data
  • Previously constructed early stopping is passed as callback to apply.
  • Class weight is passed to pay attention to under represented data.
In [38]:
relumodel.fit(
    X_train,
    y_train,
    validation_split=0.2,
    epochs=100,
    batch_size=50,
    verbose=1,
    callbacks=[earlystop],
    class_weight=class_weight,
)

Model evaluation criterion¶

What does a bank want?¶

  • A bank wants to minimize the churn too increase profitability.

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  • Predicting a customer will churn but stays with the bank.
  • Predicting a customer will not churn and the customer leaves the bank.

Which case is more important? Which loss is greater?¶

  • Predicting a customer will not churn but actually leaves the bank.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives?¶

  • Bank would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall higher the chances of minimizing false negatives. Hence, the focus should be on increasing Recall or minimizing the false negatives.

Utility function to graphically display Confusion Matrix¶

In [40]:
def make_confusion_matrix(model, test_X, y_actual, labels=[1, 0]):
    """
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    test_X: test set
    y_actual : ground truth

    """
    y_predict = model.predict(test_X)
    # Convert Predicted probabilities into binary outcome
    y_predict = (y_predict >= 0.5).astype(int)

    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(
        cm,
        index=[i for i in ["Actual - No", "Actual - Yes"]],
        columns=[i for i in ["Predicted - No", "Predicted - Yes"]],
    )
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cm.flatten() / np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in zip(group_counts, group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2, 2)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Utility function to get model metrics¶

In [41]:
def get_metrics_score(
    model, train, test, train_y, test_y, threshold=0.5, flag=True, roc=False
):
    """
    Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1 score
    model: classifier to predict values of X
    train, test: Independent features
    train_y,test_y: Dependent variable
    threshold: thresold for classifiying the observation as 1
    flag: If the flag is set to True then only the print statements showing different will be displayed. The default value is set to True.
    roc: If the roc is set to True then only roc score will be displayed. The default value is set to False.
    """
    # defining an empty list to store train and test results

    score_list = []

    pred_train = model.predict(train).ravel() > threshold
    pred_test = model.predict(test).ravel() > threshold

    pred_train = np.round(pred_train)
    pred_test = np.round(pred_test)

    train_acc = accuracy_score(pred_train, train_y)
    test_acc = accuracy_score(pred_test, test_y)

    train_recall = recall_score(train_y, pred_train)
    test_recall = recall_score(test_y, pred_test)

    train_precision = precision_score(train_y, pred_train)
    test_precision = precision_score(test_y, pred_test)

    train_f1 = f1_score(train_y, pred_train)
    test_f1 = f1_score(test_y, pred_test)

    train_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(train_y, pred_train)
    test_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(test_y, pred_test)

    score_list.extend(
        (
            train_acc,
            test_acc,
            train_recall,
            test_recall,
            train_precision,
            test_precision,
            train_f1,
            test_f1,
        )
    )

    if flag == True:
        print("Accuracy on training set : ", accuracy_score(pred_train, train_y))
        print("Accuracy on test set : ", accuracy_score(pred_test, test_y))
        print("Recall on training set : ", recall_score(train_y, pred_train))
        print("Recall on test set : ", recall_score(test_y, pred_test))
        print("Precision on training set : ", precision_score(train_y, pred_train))
        print("Precision on test set : ", precision_score(test_y, pred_test))
        print("F1 on training set : ", f1_score(train_y, pred_train))
        print("F1 on test set : ", f1_score(test_y, pred_test))

    if roc == True:
        print("ROC-AUC Score on training set : ", roc_auc_score(train_y, pred_train))
        print("ROC-AUC Score on test set : ", roc_auc_score(test_y, pred_test))

        # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Train Accuracy": train_acc,
            "Test Accuracy": test_acc,
            "Train Recall": train_recall,
            "Test Recall": test_recall,
            "Train Precision": train_precision,
            "Test Precision": test_precision,
            "Train F1": train_f1,
            "Test F1": test_f1,
            "Train ROC-AUC": train_roc_auc,
            "Test ROC-AUC": test_roc_auc,
        },
        index=[0],
    )
    return df_perf  # returning the list with train and test scores

Performance measurement using ROC-AUC¶

The Area Under the Curve (AUC) is the measure of the ability of a classifier model to distinguish between classes and is used as a summary of the ROC curve.

Check Appendix for more details.

    • Test accuracy has dropped few points from original model, which means lesser overall prediction.
    • Recall has performed very well and improved significantly, which means less incorrect predictions that customers stay in the bank.
    • Notably, Precision has dropped, which means more incorrect predictions that customers leave in the bank.
  • As we will decrease the threshold value, Recall will keep on increasing but the Precision will decrease, but that's not right because it will lead to loss of resources, we need to choose an optimal balance between recall and precision.

Evaluate Precision-Recall curve to find a better threshold¶

In [47]:
y_scores = relumodel.predict(X_test).ravel()
prec, rec, tre = precision_recall_curve(
    y_test,
    y_scores,
)


def plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], "b--", label="precision")
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], "g--", label="recall")
    plt.xlabel("Threshold")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")
    plt.ylim([0, 1])


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(prec, rec, tre)
plt.show()
  • At 0.65 threshold we get a higher recall and a good precision. i.e.
    • Good balance between recall and precision.
    • Good balance between incorrect churn and stay prediction.

Model Conclusion¶

  • Neural network model with Relu activation, has over all good prediction accuracy.
  • However, its recall score is very low, that means incorrect prediction that customer will stay but actually they churn. This must be minimized.
  • ROC-AUC and Precision-Recall curve techniques are used to find the optimal threshold to boost over all performance.
  • Optimal threshold with Precision-Recall curve seems to perform better across the board with evenly distributed score.
  • However, main purpose of the model is to find customer churn with more accuracy i.e. reduce false negative (Incorrect predictions that customers stay in the bank).
  • So we have to maximize the Recall. That means more correct prediction that customer will stay and less incorrect prediction that customer will churn.
  • Model recommendation:
    • Use neural Networks with Relu with the parameters identified during model building
    • Set the threshold to 0.465.

Business insights and key takeaways¶

  • Customer who churn has following characteristics;

    • Customer who has more than 2 bank products.
    • Non active customers.
    • Customers who live in Germany.
    • Female customers.
    • Customer who doesn't have credit card.
    • Customer who has zero balance.
    • Customer between age 45 to 60.

  • Business Recommendation

    • Product Strategy
      • Develop better customer products that are simple, affordable and easier to use.
      • Additional analysis are necessary on why customer with more than 2 products churn. More study required on the products bank offers and what triggers customers to leave when they use more bank products.
      • Internet is ubiquitous, and eventually, with proper marketing, all customers will be using online/mobile banking. So enable digital onboarding through technology and the whole onboarding process must easy and quick.
      • Prioritize and make it easy for customers to pay others quickly, invest in peer-to-peer (P2P) payment.
      • Improve time and quality of online services such as money transfer to other banks, bill pay, check deposit, etc.

    • Regional Strategy

      • Develop a geography strategy targeting regional customers.
      • For ex. Target Germany community with German site, native employees, German festival/holiday special, etc.
      • Develop regional home buyer program to target local communities.
      • Provide financial education to youth, adults, and vulnerable populations in the communities.

    • Gender Strategy

      • Develop programs such as micro lending to target business women.
      • Develop educational loan programs to engage women.

    • Usage Strategy

      • Our analysis shows that once customers get used to a banking method, they stick to it.
      • Develop and deploy loyalty programs that encourages bank usage.
      • Good customer service helps to retain the customers.

# Optimal threshold as per AUC-ROC curve

SMOTE to upsample smaller class¶

In [57]:
# To be used for over sampling
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

print("Before UpSampling, counts of label '1': {}".format(sum(y_train == 1)))
print("Before UpSampling, counts of label '0': {} \n".format(sum(y_train == 0)))

sm = SMOTE(
    sampling_strategy=1, k_neighbors=5, random_state=1
)  # Synthetic Minority Over Sampling Technique
X_train_res, y_train_res = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train.ravel())


print("After UpSampling, counts of label '1': {}".format(sum(y_train_res == 1)))
print("After UpSampling, counts of label '0': {} \n".format(sum(y_train_res == 0)))


print("After UpSampling, the shape of train_X: {}".format(X_train_res.shape))
print("After UpSampling, the shape of train_y: {} \n".format(y_train_res.shape))

importances = decisiontree.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.title("Feature Importances")
plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color="violet", align="center")

plt.xlabel("Relative Importance")
plt.show()

Conclusion:¶

  • As indicated in business insights following features determines customer churn
    • Number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.
    • Whether the customer is an active member of the bank or not
    • Estimated salary
    • Account balance
    • Customer’s location
    • Whether the customer has a credit card or not.
